'''Rev. Canon Nelson W. Pinder''' arrived in Orlando in 1959 and served the Orlando Community for more than 50 years.  He was the [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] of [[Parramore]]'s [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] of [[St. John the Baptist]] until 1997 and served on a temporary basis afterward.  He worked with white officials for peaceful [[racial integration]] in Orlando in order to avoid incidents of civil disorder that were occurring in other Florida cities during the [[Civil Rights Movement]].  Rev. Pinder organized sit-in protests of segregated lunch counters and theaters in Orlando including the [[Beacham Theatre]]. He also served a member of the [[Mayor of Orlando]] [[Bob Carr]]'s Biracial Commission which dealt with [[desegregation]] and [[equal employment]] opportunities for [[African-American]] [[citizens]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-01-08/news/os-father-pinder-recognitiion-20100108_1_episcopal-diocese-bishop-john-w-howe-episcopal-church-official |title=Episcopal diocese honors Nelson Pinder for 50 years in ministry|last1= Kunerth |first1=Jeff |date= January 8, 2010|website= |publisher=The Orlando Sentinel |access-date=August 30, 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/features/os-joy-wallace-dickinson-0927-20150927-column.html |title=Civil-rights icon Nelson Pinder: 'Orlando needed an awakening'|last1=Wallace Dickinson |first1=Joy   |date= September 27, 2015|website= |publisher=The Orlando Sentinel |access-date=August 31, 2016 |quote=}}</ref>

